Spatial Turnover Exploratory Analysis

Instructions from Malin:

Is anyone up for an exploratory analysis with the trawl data? It would be very cool to look at changes in spatial turnover, similar to Magurran, Dornelas, Moyes, Gotelli, McGill et al. 2015 but across a much wider set of regions. An idea from conversations at HIFMB yesterday.

From Magurran et al. Here, we analyse an exceptionally comprehensive 29-year time series of North Atlantic groundfish assemblages monitored over 5 latitude to the west of Scotland. These fish assemblages show no systematic change in species richness through time, but steady change in species composition, leading to an increase in spatial homogenization: the species identity of colder northern localities increasingly resembles that of warmer southern localities.

Steps would be:

  1. Calculate Jacard similarity between each haul in a single year in a single region. The vegdist() function in the vegan package would do this,OceanAdapt should have the data youd need https://github.com/pinskylab/OceanAdapt/tree/master/data_raw for NEUS files

  2. Calculate geographic distance between each haul in km (e.g., geosphere package in R could work).
  3. Plot similarity vs.geographic distance and fit a regression line.

  4. Repeat for each year.

A good place to start would just be the Northeast US. We could take a look and then think about expanding out to the other regions and to European data.

Methods from Magurran et al.

First assign the rectangles to nine 30 latitudinal bands Compile community time series for each latitudinal band Sample rarefaction ensures equal sampling effort across bands and is used in the calculation of temporal \(\alpha\) diversity and temporal \(\beta\) diversity. First calculate similarity in relation to the start of the survey Next, for each year, we compute pairwise compositional similarity of these latitudinal bands We also construct distance-decay plots for each year

latlon_reg <- na.omit(unique(neus_full.ID.regions.r, by = c("LAT", "LON")), c("LAT", "LON")) # single lat lon for each, to reduce bias, also, get rid of single NA row for Lat and Lon
# Define centroid function - Lon is first argument and Lat is second
# Geosphere takes a matrix with two columns: Lon|Lat, so we use cbind to coerce the data to this form
findCentroid <- function(LON, LAT, ...){
  centroid(cbind(LON, LAT), ...)
}
# Find centroid Lon and Lat by ID, as required
latlon_reg[, c("Cent_lon", "Cent_lat") := as.list(findCentroid(LON, LAT)), by = reg] #I will get an error on this when there are NA's in the LAT LON columns

PCA for visual

vare.pca <- rda(neus_pres_abs_1year_wide.communitymatrix[,c(1:817)])
plot(vare.pca, display = "sites")

distances_similarities_allyears <- data.table("reg1" = integer(), "reg2" = integer(), "distance(m)" = numeric(),"jaccard_similarity" = numeric(), YEAR = integer())
#Now loop through all years starting in 1967
for (i in 1:length(years)) {
  reduced_year <- neus_pres_abs[YEAR == years[i],]
  reduced_year_wide <- dcast(reduced_year, YEAR + reg ~ SCINAME, value.var = "present") #long to wide data for community matrix, column names are SVSPP
  
  communitymatrix <- cbind(reduced_year_wide[,c(3:819)], reduced_year_wide[,c(1:2)]) #community matrix
  
  
  similarities <- vegdist(communitymatrix[,c(1:817)], method = "jaccard") #similarity matrix
  #reshape similarities
  similarities.l <- melt(as.matrix(similarities), varnames = c("reg1", "reg2"))
  similarities.l <- data.table(similarities.l) #and then to data table
  similarities.l <- similarities.l[reg1 >= reg2,] # to get rid of repetitions
  colnames(similarities.l)[colnames(similarities.l)=="value"] <- "jaccard_similarity" #change column name to distance
  similarities.l[reg1 == reg2, jaccard_similarity := 1] #if they are the same value, assign jaccard_similarity of one
#add year for these values
  similarities.l[, "YEAR" := years[i]]
#merge distance with jaccard_similarity for this year
  similarities.l.full <- reg_distance.l[similarities.l, on = c("reg1", "reg2")]
distances_similarities_allyears <- rbind(distances_similarities_allyears, similarities.l.full) #add to data table
jpeg(file=paste0("jaccardplot_", years[i], ".jpg"))
    plot(x=similarities.l.full$`distance(m)`, y=similarities.l.full$jaccard_similarity, xlab = "Distance(m)", ylab="Jaccard Similarity", ylim = c(0:1), pch = 19)
 dev.off()
 
 #PCA
vare.pca <- rda(communitymatrix[,c(1:817)])
jpeg(file=paste0("jaccardpca_", years[i], ".jpg"))
plot(vare.pca, display = "sites", xlim = c(-4,4), ylim = c(-4,4))
dev.off()
  
}

  #reshape similarities
  similarities.l_GEO <- melt(as.matrix(similarities_GEO), varnames = c("year1", "year2"))
  similarities.l_GEO <- data.table(similarities.l_GEO) #and then to data table

  values_key <- c(1, rep(2:51, each=2), 52)
  year_turnover_key <- matrix(values_key, nrow = 2)
  year_turnover_key <- data.table(year_turnover_key)
  year_turnover_key.t <- transpose(year_turnover_key)
  year_turnover_key.final <- data.table("year1" = year_turnover_key.t[,V2], "year2" = year_turnover_key.t[,V1])
  
  #combine key with similarities.l_GEO
similarities_final_GEO <- year_turnover_key.final[similarities.l_GEO, on = c("year1","year2"), nomatch = 0]
